findings.lower_chest: A new, moderate right pleural effusion with adjacent atelectasis.

abdomen.hepatobiliary: The liver demonstrates homogenous attenuation throughout. There is no evidence of focal lesions. There is no evidence of intrahepatic or extrahepatic biliary dilatation.
abdomen.pancreas: The pancreas has normal attenuation throughout, without evidence of focal lesions or pancreatic ductal dilatation.
abdomen.spleen: The spleen shows normal size and attenuation throughout, without evidence of focal lesions.
abdomen.adrenals: The right and left adrenal glands are normal in size and shape.
abdomen.urinary: The kidneys are of normal and symmetric size with normal nephrogram. Multiple tiny bilateral renal hypodensities likely cysts, with the largest measuring 9 mm, unchanged since the previous study.
abdomen.gastrointestinal: Multiple contiguous loops of small bowel are fluid-filled and dilated throughout the abdomen, increased in comparison to the previous study. The appendix remains enlarged and inflamed with a small adjacent rim-enhancing fluid collection compatible with an abscess, smaller but more organized compared to the previous examination.

findings.retroperitoneum: Multiple prominent mediastinal and retroperitoneal lymph nodes are again identified, likely reactive in nature.
findings.vascular: There is no abdominal aortic aneurysm. Minimal calcium burden in the abdominal aorta and great abdominal arteries.
findings.pelvis: The urinary bladder and distal ureters are unremarkable.
findings.reproductive_organs: Redemonstrated is a fibroid uterus overall unchanged in position from the prior examination.
findings.bones_and_soft_tissues: There is no evidence of worrisome osseous lesions.

laboratory_examinations.changes_over_time: The small bowel fluid-filled status is noted to have increased in comparison to a previous study, while the adjacent abscess is now more organized and smaller compared to an earlier examination.
